---
import TruckingGuideShell from "../../../components/seo/TruckingGuideShell.astro";
import { TRUCKING_GUIDES, truckingGuideHref, TRUCKING_CALCULATOR_HREF } from "../../../data/truckingGuides";
import { DOT_MEAL_DEDUCTIBLE_FRACTION } from "../../../data/truckerPerDiemRates";

const guide = TRUCKING_GUIDES.find((g) => g.slug === "dot-80-percent-meals")!;
const pct = Math.round(DOT_MEAL_DEDUCTIBLE_FRACTION * 100);
---

<TruckingGuideShell guide={guide}>
  <h2>80% vs 50% meal deduction</h2>
  <p>
    Most taxpayers can deduct only <strong>50%</strong> of business meal expenses. Workers subject to the
    Department of Transportation <strong>hours-of-service limits</strong>—including many truck drivers—may deduct{" "}
    <strong>{pct}%</strong> instead when meals qualify.
  </p>
  <p>
    Our <a href={TRUCKING_CALCULATOR_HREF}>trucker calculator</a> applies {pct}% to the gross IRS transportation
    M&amp;IE total as a simplified planning estimate when you select &ldquo;DOT hours-of-service.&rdquo;
  </p>

  <h2>Per diem method vs actual receipts</h2>
  <p>
    Using the federal per diem method lets you substantiate the <em>amount</em> of M&amp;IE without listing every
    meal receipt, but you must still use the per diem rules correctly and only for eligible travel days.
  </p>

  <h2>Owner-operators</h2>
  <p>
    Schedule C filers often pair per diem with other deductions (fuel, depreciation, etc.). A preparer can help
    decide between per diem and actual expenses for meals.
  </p>

  <h2>Related</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><a href={truckingGuideHref("irs-transportation-rates")}>IRS transportation rates</a></li>
  </ul>
</TruckingGuideShell>
